\title{Digit replacement dynamics: A toy model for strange nonchaotic attractors} 










\author{Vladimir Garc\'{\i}a-Morales}
\email[]{garmovla@uv.es}




\affiliation{Departament de Termodin\`amica, Universitat de Val\`encia, E-46100 Burjassot, Spain}


\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
\noindent A simple discontinuous map is proposed as a toy model for strange nonchaotic attractors (SNAs). The orbit of the map admits exact solutions for wide regions in parameter space and allows SNAs to be mathematically designed in a straightforward manner. Besides SNAs, the  method employed (digit manipulation) allows useful signals, such as oscillations with specific waveforms and different basins of attraction in phase space with different qualitative properties, to be constructed. 
\end{abstract}

\pacs{02.70.Bf, 05.45.Ac, 05.45.Df}

\maketitle 












\section{Introduction}

A nonlinear dynamical system driven by an irrational ratio of frequencies generically displays a dynamics between order and chaos, giving rise to strange nonchaotic attractors (SNAs). A SNA is a fractal structure attracting the trajectories in phase space so that the dynamics of the system is not exponentially sensitive to initial conditions. The existence of SNAs was first pointed out in a seminal paper by Grebogi, Ott, Pelikan and Yorke \cite{Grebogi} and have been widely studied since then \cite{Feudel1, Feudel2, HuntO, Yalcinkaya, Prasad}. Experimentally, SNAs were first discovered in the buckling of a magnetoelastic ribbon driven quasiperiodically by two incommensurate frequencies with the golden ratio relationship \cite{Ditto}. Since then they have also been reported in other laboratory experiments involving electrochemical cells \cite{Parmananda}, electronic circuits \cite{Zhou}, and a neon glow discharge \cite{Ding}. Recently, based on the unprecedented light curves of the Kepler space telescope, SNAs have also been observed for the first time   
out of the laboratory in the dynamics of the RRc Lyrae star KIC 5520878, a blue-white star 16 000 light years from Earth in the constellation Lyra \cite{Lindner}. 

In this article we formulate a toy model for strange non-chaotic attractors (SNAs). \cite{Grebogi,Feudel1, Feudel2} Since the model has the form of a discontinuous map with certain peculiar properties, a few remarks are necessary in order to appropriately place the model in a rigorous mathematical context. A dynamical system \cite{Lind} is a pair $(M, \phi)$, where $M$ is a compact metric space and $\phi$ a continuous map $\phi: M \to M$. Differential and difference equations provide prominent examples of (nonlinear) dynamical systems \cite{May, Feigenbaum, RuelleEckmann}. In these, the compact metric space is usually a closed subset of the Euclidean space and the maps are polynomials of the dynamical variable, which become normal forms in characterizing universality classes and bifurcations. Other dynamical systems are cellular automata \cite{Lind, Hedlund, Wolfram, VGM1}, which act on the shift space. In this article we study a class of simple first-order difference equations $\phi: M \to M$ where the underlying compact space is constituted by arbitrary closed intervals of the real line but where $\phi$ is discontinuous. Thus, the resulting pair $(M, \phi)$ would not rigorously qualify as a dynamical system. However, since these features can be generally understood as arising from a `caricature' of a continuous map on a compact metric space in a precise sense (because of the existence of a direct mathematical method connecting the original dynamical system to its caricature, that we present here) we propose this class of maps as a possible toy model for nonlinear dynamical systems in general, and SNAs in particular. Some advantages of this formulation are discussed. We find that the shape of the oscillations on an attracting limit cycle can be mathematically engineered. We introduce a mathematical method for the digit manipulation of the numerical values of the relevant dynamical variable and show how our toy model can indeed be derived starting from any arbitrary non-autonomous map. The method allows the mathematical design/modeling of time series with complex waveforms.



This article is organized as follows. In Section \ref{digit} we briefly introduce the main mathematical tools, the digit function and the replacement operator, in which our approach is based. Then, we derive our main result which constitutes a mathematical means to convert an arbitrary non-autonomous map into the general map that is the object of our study (see Eq. (\ref{absmap}) below). Then in Section \ref{maphor} we discuss in detail its dynamics,  providing explicit closed forms or detailed insight of the orbits of the map. This discussion culminates in the model for SNAs. We show how different SNAs can be created in phase space, all sharing aspects of the same qualitative dynamics, even when they are distinguishable. The basins of attractions are trivial in every case and are exactly determined. Although we not explicitly use any explicit frequency ratio to construct the attractors, our approach highlights the importance of irrational numbers in the dynamics on SNAs.




